SIMPLE: sequacious
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sequacious
<hw>Se*qua"cious</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>sequax</ets>, <ets>-acis</ets>, fr. <ets>suquit</ets> to follow.
See <er>Sue</er> to follow. ]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Inclined to follow
a leader; following; attendant.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Trees uprooted left their place,⟦br⟧
<qex>Sequacious</qex> of the lyre.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, ductile; malleable; pliant;
manageable.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In the greater bodies the forge was easy, the matter being ductile
and <qex>sequacious</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Ray.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Having or observing logical sequence; logically
consistent and rigorous; consecutive in development or transition of
thought.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The scheme of pantheistic omniscience so prevalent among the
<qex>sequacious</qex> thinkers of the day.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Hamilton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Milton was not an extensive or discursive thinker, as Shakespeare
was; for the motions of his mind were slow, solemn, and
<qex>sequacious</qex>, like those of the planets.</q> <rj><qau>De
Quincey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sequaciousness</ent>⟦br⟧
